{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521506"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13688"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13688"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.09,0.12,0.22,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52350"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6296"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13688"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10977"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46056"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52350"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a two-week history of painful red lumps on her shins, a low-grade fever, and pain and swelling in both ankles. She also reports mild shortness of breath and a dry cough for the past few days. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There are multiple raised, red, tender nodules on the anterior aspects of both shins. No other skin lesions are noted. Examination of her ankles reveals mild swelling and tenderness. The small joints of her hands are normal. Respiratory examination reveals scattered crackles in both lung bases. Her biochemistry and full blood count results are normal. Chest x-ray and thoracic CT scans are taken (Images 1-2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following eponymous syndromes is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Beh\u00e7et syndrome","Felty syndrome","Reiter syndrome","Churg-Strauss syndrome","L\u00f6fgren syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor better or worse, eponyms and eponymous syndromes have been a part of medicine throughout its history and are likely to remain so for the foreseeable future. This case deals with some relatively common syndromes (at least in textbooks and exams).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EL\u00f6fgren syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, which is an acute form of sarcoidosis. The classic triad of L\u00f6fgren syndrome includes erythema nodosum (painful red nodules on the shins), bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy (as demonstrated on CXR and CT in this case), and arthritis (in this case, affecting the ankles). The absence of other skin lesions and normal hand joints support this diagnosis. L\u00f6fgren syndrome has a good prognosis, with spontaneous remission usually occurring within 2 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeh\u00e7et syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a systemic vasculitis that can cause oral and genital ulcers, uveitis, and skin lesions. While arthritis can be a feature, the other manifestations of Beh\u00e7et syndrome are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe normal full blood examination helps exclude eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA) (also known as \u003Cstrong\u003EChurg-Strauss syndrome)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by eosinophilia. EGPA is a small vessel vasculitis typically presenting with asthma, peripheral eosinophilia, and vasculitic manifestations. Patients often have a history of adult-onset asthma, allergic rhinitis, and sinusitis. The vasculitic phase can involve the skin (purpura, nodules), peripheral nerves (mononeuritis multiplex), heart (myocarditis, pericarditis), and gastrointestinal tract. The absence of asthma, eosinophilia, and these systemic features makes EGPA unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFelty syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by rheumatoid arthritis, splenomegaly and neutropenia. The arthritis in Felty syndrome typically affects the small joints of the hands and feet. While this patient has arthritis, she does not have the other features of Felty syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReiter syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as reactive arthritis, can cause arthritis, urethritis and conjunctivitis. However, erythema nodosum and hilar lymphadenopathy are not typical features.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["L\u00f6fgren syndrome is an acute form of sarcoidosis characterised by erythema nodosum, bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy and arthritis.","L\u00f6fgren syndrome has a good prognosis with spontaneous remission usually occurring within two years."],"references":["Flores R, Caridade S. L\u00f6fgren Syndrome: Clinical Presentation, Clinical Course, and Literature Review. Cureus. 2023 Jan 11;15(1):e33651. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9912994/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13688"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20644"},{"type":"media","id":"20698"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20644"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VlJCqFYzDdPGtX74GB3EdDQpDbxxsk.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VlJCqFYzDdPGtX74GB3EdDQpDbxxsk.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":397,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20698"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9IFngrDC6UTt0F4IWqH1kg6YKp9LQ7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9IFngrDC6UTt0F4IWqH1kg6YKp9LQ7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":551,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-03T21:23:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-01T08:41:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6296"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52350"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"it